In [22]:
# we can now conduct global and local Moran's I and map them
# defining spatial weight using Queen's method
wq =  lp.weights.Queen.from_dataframe(peel_wellbeing)
wq.transform = 'r'

# defining spatial weight using Rooke's method
wr =  lp.weights.Rook.from_dataframe(peel_wellbeing)
wr.transform = 'r'

# assigning a column field value 
y = peel_wellbeing["Overall Wellbeing"]
In [23]:
# running global Moran's I for Queen's
np.random.seed(1234)
queen_mi = esda.moran.Moran(y, wq)
queen_mi.I
queen_mi.EI

# plotting global MI for Queen's
sbn.kdeplot(queen_mi.sim, fill=True)
plt.vlines(queen_mi.I, 0, 1, color='r')
plt.vlines(queen_mi.EI, 0,1)
plt.xlabel("Global Moran's I for Overall Wellbeing (Queen's)");

In [25]:
# running local Moran's I for Queen's
np.random.seed(1234)
wq.transform = 'r'
wellbeing_q = lp.weights.lag_spatial(wq, y)


overall_wellbeing_q = peel_wellbeing['Overall Wellbeing']
b, a = np.polyfit(overall_wellbeing_q, wellbeing_q, 1)
f, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(9, 9))

plt.plot(overall_wellbeing_q, wellbeing_q, '.', color='firebrick')

 # dashed vert at mean of wellbeing
plt.vlines(overall_wellbeing_q.mean(), wellbeing_q.min(), wellbeing_q.max(), linestyle='--')
 # dashed horizontal at mean of lagged wellbeing
plt.hlines(wellbeing_q.mean(), overall_wellbeing_q.min(), overall_wellbeing_q.max(), linestyle='--')

# red line of best fit using global I as slope
plt.plot(overall_wellbeing_q, a + b*overall_wellbeing_q, 'r')
plt.title('Moran Scatterplot')
plt.ylabel('Spatial Lag of Wellbeing')
plt.xlabel('Wellbeing')
plt.show()

np.random.seed(1234)

 # dashed vert at mean of wellbeing

In [27]:
local_q = esda.moran.Moran_Local(y, wq)


# sum of values < 0.05 level of statistical signficance
(local_q.p_sim < 0.05).sum()

# types of local clusters in MI plot
sig = local_q.p_sim < 0.05
hotspot = sig * local_q.q==1
coldspot = sig * local_q.q==3
doughnut = sig * local_q.q==2
diamond = sig * local_q.q==4

#hot spots
spots = ['n.sig.', 'hot spot']
labels = [spots[i] for i in hotspot*1]

# cold spots
spots = ['n.sig.', 'cold spot']
labels = [spots[i] for i in coldspot*1]
In [28]:
# plotting both hot and cold spots on one map
sig = 1 * (local_q.p_sim < 0.05)
hotspot = 1 * (sig * local_q.q==1)
coldspot = 3 * (sig * local_q.q==3)

spots = hotspot + coldspot


spot_labels = [ '0 Not Significant', '1 Hot Spot', '2 doughnut', '3 Cold Spot', '4 diamond']
labels = [spot_labels[i] for i in spots]

from matplotlib import colors
hmap = colors.ListedColormap([ 'lightgrey', 'red', 'blue',])
f, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(9, 9))
peel_wellbeing.assign(cl=labels).plot(column='cl', categorical=True, \
        k=2, cmap=hmap, linewidth=0.1, ax=ax, \
        edgecolor='white', legend=True)
ax.set_axis_off()
plt.title("Hot and Cold Spots Map for Queen's")
plt.show()
